          "body": "The first object specified is the ark — a chest of acacia wood completely overlaid with pure gold, fitted with permanent carrying poles and designed to house the 'testimony' (edut, the covenant tablets). The physical arrangement is theologically exact: the law (25:16) goes inside the ark; the mercy seat (kapporet, 25:17) goes on top. Atonement covers the law. On Yom Kippur, the high priest would sprinkle blood on the mercy seat (Leviticus 16:14-15) — the blood of substitutionary sacrifice applied to the lid of the chest that contained the covenant's demands. Paul sees this as the antitype pointing to Christ: 'God displayed Him publicly as a propitiation in His blood' (Romans 3:25 NASB), using the LXX's hilasterion — the word the Greek Old Testament uses for kapporet. The mercy seat is the most concentrated christological object in the Pentateuch. The cherubim whose wings overshadow it (25:20) have their faces turned toward it — all of heaven's attention fixed on the place where justice and mercy meet."
