        "excerpt": "You shall set the bread of the Presence on the table before Me at all times.",
        "body": "The table of acacia wood overlaid with pure gold (25:23-24) is the second piece of inner-sanctum furniture. Its dimensions (two cubits long, one cubit wide, one and a half cubits high — roughly 36 × 18 × 27 inches) make it proportionally smaller than the ark but designed for active use: dishes, pans, jars, and bowls for drink offerings (25:29) indicate a fully equipped dining surface. This is not symbolic furniture; it is functional furniture placed in the presence of God.\n\nThe Bread of the Presence (lechem panim, 'bread of the face' or 'bread of the presence') is the table's perpetual content (25:30). Twelve loaves representing the twelve tribes of Israel were kept before God 'at all times' (tamid). The priests replaced them every Sabbath and ate the replaced loaves in the Holy Place (Leviticus 24:5-9). The arrangement is a covenantal meal: Israel is fed at God's table; Israel is represented before God's face. The bread is never absent; the table is never empty. The tamid language echoes the 'at all times' of the lampstand (27:20) and the daily burnt offering (29:42) — God's provision for His people is a permanent, uninterrupted arrangement.\n\nThe theological logic of the table stands in deliberate contrast to the manna of the wilderness. Manna could not be stored (Exodus 16:19-20) — it was a daily provision requiring daily dependence. The Bread of the Presence, by contrast, remains before God continuously. What is brought into God's immediate presence is preserved. The eschatological implications are drawn out in Luke 22:29-30, where Jesus promises the disciples 'a kingdom, just as My Father has granted Me a kingdom, that you may eat and drink at My table in My kingdom.' The table of the Presence prefigures the eschatological banquet of Revelation 19:9.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Lechem panim* (Bread of the Presence) — literally 'bread of the face.' The dual meaning of *panim* (face/presence) captures both the personal — this is bread before God's face — and the spatial — it is set in the zone of His immediate presence. *Tamid* (at all times, always) — an adverb of perpetuity used throughout the Levitical code to describe the permanent standing orders of the tabernacle cultus. It will govern the daily burnt offering (29:42), the lampstand's oil (27:20), and the incense altar (30:8)."
